scape and respond effectively to individual and collective challenges. Integral Theory in Action provides the first multi-authored overview of such an approach. Integral Theory is the result of 30 years of research and is being applied in over 35 distinct disciplines. This volume brings together two dozen leading scholar-practitioners who are actively applying integral principles and who address a range of issues from an integral perspective including: climate change, embodiment, feminist aesthetics, community discourse, treatment of depression, developmental theory, and global ethics. The strengths, limitations, and potential of Integral Theory and Ken Wilber's AQAL model are weighed by each contributor. This collection pushes the field of Integral Theory in new ways and new directions, and provides a comprehensive overview that makes it an invaluable resource for any integral effort.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aInterdisciplinary research. 0aSocial sciencesxResearchxMethodology. 4aPsychology : Developmental Psychology. 4aPsychology : Humanistic Psychology. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Spirituality. 4aSociology : Systems Analysis. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Applied Psychology.2bisacsh1 aChase, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook-Greuter, Cook-Greuter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsbjörn-Hargens, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsbjörn-Hargens, Sean, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFisher, Vanessa D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlores, Charles I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForman, Mark D., ec